From b0356ed0dce772a58fe829ecd2814fb2d56e7d52 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Gravio <gravio@uni-muenster.de>
Date: Wed, 29 Apr 2026 17:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] feature_subsets refactor step 6: video-level parallelization
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Step 6 (final step) of AUDIT_feature_subsets_calculator.md.
Adds opt-in parallel execution via concurrent.futures.ProcessPoolExecutor.

Default behavior (n_workers=1) is unchanged from step 5: sequential
processing of videos in order. Parallel mode (n_workers > 1) is
strictly opt-in via constructor argument.

WHY THIS WAS HARD AND WHY IT SHOULD BE TREATED CAREFULLY:

This is the highest-risk step in the refactor. Without ground-truth
verification of step 1's output equivalence (which would require
running smoke_feature_kernels_realdata.py against a pre-refactor
saved feature output), parallel correctness is verified only by:

1. AST-level checks (the parallel path exists, uses
   ProcessPoolExecutor, the config is a frozen dataclass)
2. Picklability of VideoProcessingConfig (verified by manually
   pickling a representative instance — ~1.6 KB serialized,
   round-trips cleanly)
3. The new tests/smoke_feature_parallel_verify.py script which
   the user must run on the workstation to compare sequential
   and parallel output byte-equivalently.

THE USER MUST RUN smoke_feature_parallel_verify.py BEFORE TRUSTING
n_workers > 1 FOR PRODUCTION ANALYSIS.

What changed:

1. MODIFIED: mufasa/feature_extractors/feature_subsets.py
   - Added two new constructor parameters:
     * n_workers: int = 1 (positive int, validated in __init__)
       1 = sequential (default, byte-equivalent to step 5).
       >1 = use ProcessPoolExecutor with that many workers.
     * raise_on_error: bool = False
       False (default) = on per-video failure in parallel mode,
         log to stderr and continue with remaining videos. Print
         a summary at the end. Useful for batch processing where
         one bad video shouldn't kill 66 others.
       True = on first failure, cancel pending futures and re-raise
         the exception. Strict-mode equivalent of sequential
         behavior.
   - run() now branches on self.n_workers <= 1 to call
     either _run_sequential or _run_parallel.
   - NEW METHOD _run_sequential: extracted from old run() body
     into a separate method. Behavior unchanged.
   - NEW METHOD _run_parallel: builds a futures dict, processes
     completions via as_completed, collects per-video failures.

2. MODIFIED: tests/smoke_feature_kernels.py
   - NEW CASES 11-12:
     * Verify _run_parallel and _run_sequential methods exist
       on the class
     * Verify _run_parallel uses ProcessPoolExecutor (not
       just threads or some other backend)
     * Verify VideoProcessingConfig is decorated as
       @dataclass(frozen=True) — the picklability contract
   - Test count: 12/12 cases passed.

3. NEW: tests/smoke_feature_parallel_verify.py
   - User-runnable on workstation. Picks N test videos, runs
     them once sequential, once parallel (with N workers), and
     compares output byte-equivalently. This is the gold-standard
     verification of the parallel implementation.
   - NOT runnable in sandbox.

Performance expectations:

On Ryzen 9800X3D (8 physical cores, 16 SMT threads):
- n_workers=8 should give 5-7× speedup on the user's typical
  67-video workload (ceiling is below 8× because of disk I/O
  contention on read_df + write_df).
- 4-hour sequential → ~35-45 min parallel.
- First parallel run pays an ~8-second numba JIT warm-up tax
  per worker (~64 seconds total). Subsequent runs use the
  cached compilations and skip warm-up.

What this DOES NOT change:

- Sequential behavior: byte-equivalent to step 5. The default
  flag is n_workers=1.
- Public API: existing callers in mufasa.ui.pop_ups and
  mufasa.ui_qt.forms.features continue working without
  modification (they don't pass n_workers, so they get the
  default of 1).
- Per-video output bytes: byte-identical between sequential
  and parallel modes WHEN PARALLELIZATION IS CORRECT. The
  whole point of the verification script is to confirm this
  empirically.

What might still need attention:

- numba cache directory: workers re-JIT kernels on first call.
  The cache is shared across workers (it's in the user's home
  ~/.numba_cache or whatever). After the first parallel run,
  subsequent runs reuse compiled kernels without re-JITing.
- File contention: workers write to `temp_dir/<video>.parquet`
  and each video has a unique filename, so there is no write
  contention. But with 8 workers all writing simultaneously on
  the same NVMe device, IO performance may bottleneck before
  CPU does. Realistic scaling tops out around 6-7×.
- Memory: each worker holds a full pose dataframe in memory
  (~few hundred MB) plus numba intermediate buffers. With 8
  workers on a 64 GB workstation, this is ~5-10 GB total. Well
  within budget, but worth monitoring with htop the first time
  the user runs n_workers=8.

REQUIRED FOLLOWUP BY THE USER:

1. Run tests/smoke_feature_parallel_verify.py with --config
   pointing at the project_config.ini and --n-test-videos 4.
   If "Parallelization VERIFIED" → safe to use n_workers > 1.
2. If verification fails, DO NOT use n_workers > 1 for the
   actual research data. The output is potentially wrong.
   Stop and investigate the diff.

The refactor is complete after this patch. Steps 1-6 done.
